INDEPENDENT AUDITOR’S REPORT
Plan Administrator and Plan Participants
Wells Fargo & Company Cash Balance Plan
Scope and Nature of the ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C) Audit
We have performed audits of the financial statements of Wells Fargo & Company Cash Balance Plan (the Plan),
an employee benefit plan subject to the Employee Retirement Income Security Act of 1974 (ERISA), as permitted
by ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C) (ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C) audit). The financial statements comprise the
statements of net assets available for benefits as of December 31, 2024 and 2023, and the related statement of
changes in net assets available for benefits for the year ended December 31, 2024, and the related notes to the
financial statements.
Management, having determined it is permissible in the circumstances, has elected to have the audits of the
Plan’s financial statements performed in accordance with ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C) pursuant to 29 CFR
2520.103-8 of the Department of Labor's Rules and Regulations for Reporting and Disclosure under ERISA. As
permitted by ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C), our audits need not extend to any statements or information related to
assets held for investment of the plan (investment information) by a bank or similar institution or insurance carrier
that is regulated, supervised, and subject to periodic examination by a state or federal agency, provided that the
statements or information regarding assets so held are prepared and certified to by the bank or similar institution
or insurance carrier in accordance with 29 CFR 2520.103-5 of the Department of Labor's Rules and Regulations
for Reporting and Disclosure under ERISA (qualified institution).
Management has obtained certifications from an agent on behalf of the qualified institution as of December 31,
2024 and 2023, and for the year ended December 31, 2024, stating that the certified investment information, as
described in Note 5 to the financial statements, is complete and accurate.
Opinion
In our opinion, based on our audits and on the procedures performed as described in the Auditor's

• the amounts and disclosures in the accompanying financial statements, other than those agreed to or

Responsibilities of Management for the Financial Statements
Management is responsible for the preparation and fair presentation of the financial statements in accordance
with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America, and for the design,

statements that are free from material misstatement, whether due to fraud or error. Management's election of the

In preparing the financial statements, management is required to evaluate whether there are conditions or events,

Management is also responsible for maintaining a current plan instrument, including all plan amendments,
administering the plan, and determining that the plan's transactions that are presented and disclosed in the
financial statements are in conformity with the plan's provisions, including maintaining sufficient records with
respect to each of the participants, to determine the benefits due or which may become due to such participants.
Auditor’s Responsibilities for the Audit of the Financial Statements
Except as described in the Scope and Nature of the ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C) Audit section of our report, our
objectives are to obtain reasonable assurance about whether the financial statements as a whole are free from
material misstatement, whether due to fraud or error, and to issue an auditor's report that includes our opinion.
Reasonable assurance is a high level of assurance but is not absolute assurance and therefore is not a guarantee
that an audit conducted in accordance with GAAS will always detect a material misstatement when it exists. The
risk of not detecting a material misstatement resulting from fraud is higher than for one resulting from error, as
fraud may involve collusion, forgery, intentional omissions, misrepresentations, or the override of internal control.
Misstatements are considered material if, there is a substantial likelihood that, individually or in the aggregate,
they would influence the judgment made by a reasonable user based on the financial statements.
In performing an audit in accordance with GAAS, we:
• Exercise professional judgment and maintain professional skepticism throughout the audit.
• Identify and assess the risks of material misstatement of the financial statements, whether due to fraud
or error, and design and perform audit procedures responsive to those risks. Such procedures include

effectiveness of the Plan’s internal control. Accordingly, no such opinion is expressed.
• Evaluate the appropriateness of accounting policies used and the reasonableness of significant
accounting estimates made by management, as well as evaluate the overall presentation of the financial
statements.
• Conclude whether, in our judgment, there are conditions or events, considered in the aggregate, that
raise substantial doubt about the Plan’s ability to continue as a going concern for a reasonable period
of time.

(1) Description of the Plan
The following description of the Wells Fargo & Company Cash Balance Plan (the “Plan”) provides
only general information. Participants should refer to the Plan document for a more complete
description of the Plan’s provisions. Wells Fargo & Company (the “Company”) is the Plan Sponsor.
(a) General
Effective July 1, 1999, the Plan then known as the “Norwest Corporation Pension Plan” was
amended and restated to change it from a traditional final average pay defined benefit plan
to a cash balance plan and to change the name of the Plan to the “Wells Fargo & Company
Cash Balance Plan.” Since July 1, 1999, the Plan has been amended to take into
consideration various tax law changes including required changes under the Pension
Protection Act of 2006, to address certain Plan design changes, and to address certain
acquisitions and plan mergers.
The Plan is administered by the Plan Sponsor’s Head of Human Resources (or the functional
equivalent title of the most senior position in Human Resources), the Head of Total Rewards
(or the functional equivalent title of the most senior position in Human Resources over
compensation and benefit plans or programs other than the Head of Human Resources),
and the Head of Benefits (or the functional equivalent title of the most senior position in
Human Resources over benefit plans and programs other than the Head of Human
Resources and the Head of Total Rewards), each of whom may act individually or jointly as
the Plan Administrator, or its or their authorized delegate. The Employee Benefit Review
Committee has the authority to control and manage the assets of the Plan.
Effective July 1, 2009, the Plan was “frozen” and no additional benefits have been accrued
for any participants. Benefits earned prior to July 1, 2009 are not affected by the Plan
freeze. Participants’ cash balance accounts will continue to be allocated investment credits
after June 30, 2009 until distribution; however, no additional compensation credits will be
allocated to participants’ accounts. There are no new participants after June 30, 2009 and
no participants are considered “Active Participants” for periods beginning on or after July 1,
2009.
Prior to July 1, 2009, employees were eligible to participate in the Plan the first day of the
quarter after completing one year of service with the Company. Pension benefits are
determined by the value of a participant’s vested Plan cash balance account.
Effective January 1, 2024, the Plan was amended (Amendment 2023-02) to increase the
applicable limit regarding Payment of Small Benefits from $4,000 to $7,000. If the
participant does not make an election by the end of the applicable election period, the
benefit will automatically be distributed as a direct rollover to an individual retirement
account that meets the Department of Labor (“DOL”) safe-harbor requirements.
Effective January 1, 2024, the Plan was amended (Amendment 2023-01) to revise the
definition of the “applicable interest rates” used in an Actuarial Equivalent calculation.
(b) Participants’ Accounts
Prior to July 1, 2009 (the date the Plan froze), compensation credits and investment credits
were allocated to eligible participants’ hypothetical Plan accounts at the end of every
quarter. The compensation credits were allocated based on a percentage of each
participant’s certified compensation for that particular quarter. The applicable percentage

ranges were from 3% to 7% after January 1, 2004 and 4% to 8% before January 1, 2004 and
were based on the participants’ age plus years of credited service (as defined by the Plan) at
the end of the quarter. Age and credited service are determined in whole years at the end of

Participants’ accounts continue to receive investment credits at the end of every quarter
even though the Plan is frozen. The amount of the investment credit is tied to the average
of the annual yields on 30-year constant maturity treasury securities and is adjusted every
quarter. The initial interest rate used for the investment credit is 25% of the average of the
annual yields on 30-year constant maturity treasury securities for the three months
preceding the first day of the quarter. As of both December 31, 2024 and 2023, the
quarterly interest rate was 1.06%.
(c) Funding Policy
The Company makes all contributions to the Plan. Participants are not allowed to make
contributions. Each plan year, the Plan’s actuary determines the range of acceptable
contributions to the Plan and the amount the Company must fund as prescribed by the
Employee Retirement Income Security Act of 1974, as amended (“ERISA”). During 2024,
the Company did not make any contributions to the Plan. Additionally, the Company may
make annual contributions to the 401(h) account based upon the maximum deductibility
under the Internal Revenue Code (“IRC”).
Although the Company has not expressed any intention to do so, the Company has the right
under the Plan to terminate the Plan subject to the provisions set forth in ERISA.
The Wells Fargo & Company Master Pension Trust (the “Trust”) is used to fund benefits
under the Plan. Delaware Charter Guarantee & Trust Company, conducting business under
the trade name “Principal Trust Company”, is the trustee of the Trust (the “Trustee”).
Principal Bank, an affiliate of Principal Trust Company, serves as an agent for Principal Trust
Company, and is the qualified certifying institution of the financial information for the Plan.
The Trustee executes purchases and sales of investments in the Trust pursuant to the
direction of the Employee Benefit Review Committee or its agent. The investments of the
Trust and the changes therein have been reported to the Plan by the Trustee.
(d) Benefits
Benefits are determined based on the participant’s Plan account. Under the terms of the
Plan, participants are eligible for their Plan benefit after terminating employment with
vested rights. Participants become vested in the Plan upon completion of three years of
vesting service or attainment of age 65. Upon termination of employment, participants
have the option of receiving their vested Plan account payable in the form of a one-time
lump-sum payment or a monthly annuity payable for their lifetime. Participants may elect
to defer payment of their benefit until a later date (if the value of the accrued benefit is
greater than $7,000 as of January 1, 2024). Participants eligible for a special transition
benefit will have their final benefits determined at the time they elect to begin receiving
payments from the Plan. Any adjustment for the special transition benefit calculation is
automatically determined and communicated to the participants. Active participants who
die will automatically become vested in the Plan, and their account will be paid to their
designated beneficiary.

To transition from the prior final average pay formula design to the cash balance design,
initial account balances were established for eligible participants who had earned a benefit
under the Plan when it was known as the Norwest Corporation Pension Plan (the “Norwest
benefit”) and for eligible participants in the First Interstate Bank Plan (the “FIB Plan”) prior
to the conversion. Initial account balances were determined as follows:
(i) For eligible employees participating in the Plan on June 30, 1999, and actively
participating on July 1, 1999, the initial account balances were determined by
converting the participants’ monthly Norwest benefit payable at “regular retirement
age” into a lump-sum value as of July 1, 1999. Several assumptions were used when
determining the monthly Norwest benefit to be used in the conversion. These
assumptions included (but were not limited to) using credited service through June 30,
1999, certified compensation through December 31, 1998, and the 1998 integration
level, which is 35% of the social security wage base.
(ii) For eligible employees participating in the FIB Plan on June 30, 1999, and actively
participating in this Plan on July 1, 1999, initial account balances were determined by
converting employees’ frozen monthly FIB Plan benefits payable at normal retirement
age into lump-sum values as of July 1, 1999. Accrued benefits for former employees of
the FIB Plan who were no longer employees of the Company as of June 30, 1999, or
who were not active participants in this Plan as of July 1, 1999, continue to be frozen
and were not converted to an initial account balance in the Plan.
Employees who were active participants in the Plan on July 1, 1999, and were at least age 45
with 5 or more years of credited service as of June 30, 1999, became eligible for a special
“transition benefit” under the Plan. This transition benefit was established to ensure that
eligible participants would receive the same benefit or a larger benefit than they would have
under the Norwest benefit formula. In general, for participants who met the age 45 with
5 years of credited service requirements and had a Norwest benefit, the transition benefit
calculation provides the greater of the Plan account or the benefit determined under the
Norwest benefit final average pay formula. For participants who met the age 45 with 5 years
of credited service requirements and were previously participants in the FIB Plan, the
transition benefit calculation provides an adjustment to the Plan account if the lump-sum
value of the frozen FIB benefit determined as of a participant’s commencement date
(including early retirement subsidies) is greater than the Plan account accumulated with
investment credits only.
(e) Annuity Contracts
The Company entered into several group annuity contracts from 1986 through 1988 with
various insurance providers for certain individual participants of the Plan. Purchased
annuities are contracts under which the insurance providers are obligated to pay benefits to
individually named employees or their beneficiaries. Because these contracts are fully
allocated to individual participants, the Plan does not recognize the related assets or
obligations in its financial statements. The Plan received no dividend income from such
contracts in either 2024 or 2023.

(2) Summary of Significant Accounting Policies
(a) Basis of Presentation
The accounting records of the Plan are maintained, and the accompanying financial
statements have been prepared, on the accrual basis of accounting in conformity with
accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America.
(b) Investments and Income Recognition
Purchases and sales of securities are recorded on the trade-date basis. Interest income is
recorded on the accrual basis. Dividends are recorded on the ex-dividend date. Net
depreciation includes gains and losses on investments bought and sold as well as held during
the year.
(c) Fair Value - Definition and Hierarchy
Investments are reported at fair value. Fair value is defined as the price that would be
received to sell an asset or paid to transfer a liability in an orderly transaction between
market participants at the measurement date. Fair value is based on an exit price notion
that maximizes the use of observable inputs and minimizes the use of unobservable inputs.
The Plan classifies its assets and liabilities measured at fair value based upon a three-level
hierarchy that assigns the highest priority to unadjusted quoted prices in active markets and
the lowest priority to unobservable inputs. The three levels are as follows:
• Level 1 – Valuation is based upon quoted prices for identical instruments traded in
active markets.
• Level 2 – Valuation is based upon quoted prices for similar instruments in active
markets, quoted prices for identical or similar instruments in markets that are not
active, and model-based valuation techniques, for which all significant assumptions
are observable in the market.
• Level 3 – Valuation is generated from techniques that use significant assumptions not
observable in the market. These unobservable assumptions reflect estimates of
assumptions that market participants would use in pricing the asset or liability.
Valuation techniques include use of discounted cash flow models, market comparable
pricing, option models, and similar techniques.
Derivatives are valued at fair value (Note 7).
(d) Risks and Uncertainties
The Plan may invest in various types of investment securities. Investment securities are
exposed to various risks such as interest rate, market, and credit risks. Due to the level of
risk associated with certain investment securities, it is at least reasonably possible that
changes in the values of investment securities will occur in the near term and that such
changes could materially affect the amounts reported in the statements of net assets
available for benefits.
Plan contributions are made and the actuarial present value of accumulated plan benefits
are reported based on certain assumptions pertaining to interest rates, inflation rates, and
employee demographics, all of which are subject to change. Due to uncertainties inherent in
the estimations and assumptions process, it is at least reasonably possible that changes in

(3) Actuarial Present Value of Accumulated Plan Benefits
Accumulated plan benefits are those future periodic payments, including lump-sum distributions,
which are attributable under the Plan’s provisions to the service employees have rendered.
Accumulated plan benefits include benefits expected to be paid to (a) retired or terminated
participants or their beneficiaries; (b) beneficiaries of participants who have died; and (c) active
participants. Benefits under the Plan for participants who have cash balance accounts are based
on a percentage of the participants’ certified compensation and investment credits allocated to
their cash balance account. Special transition benefits apply to certain eligible participants who
were at least age 45 with at least five years of credited service as of June 30, 1999. Benefits
payable under all circumstances – retirement, death, disability, and termination of employment –
are included to the extent they are deemed attributable to employee service rendered to the
valuation date.
The actuarial present value of accumulated plan benefits is determined by an independent actuary
and is that amount, which results from applying actuarial assumptions to adjust the accumulated
plan benefits to reflect the time value of money (through discounts for interest) and the
probability of payment (by means of decrements such as for death, disability, withdrawal, or
retirement) between the valuation date and the expected date of payment.

(4) Plan Termination
Pursuant to ERISA requirements, if a termination is the result of the bankruptcy or near
bankruptcy of the Plan Sponsor and the Plan’s assets are not adequate to pay all benefits vested
prior to the termination, the PBGC will take over the Plan and pay those benefits, which it
guarantees. In this case, some participants may receive a smaller benefit than if the Plan had
continued. Whether a particular participant’s accumulated plan benefits will be paid depends on
both the priority of those benefits and the level of benefits guaranteed by the PBGC at that time.
If the Plan terminates due to bankruptcy or near bankruptcy of the Plan Sponsor, and if the Plan
assets are not adequate to provide for all benefits accrued, whether vested or not, the priorities of
distribution of Plan assets are to (a) provide that portion of each individual’s accrued benefit that
is derived from the participant’s mandatory contribution to the Plan, if any; (b) provide benefits

(6) Fair Value Measurements
The Plan classifies its investments recorded at fair value as either Level 1, 2, or 3 in the fair value
hierarchy. The highest priority (Level 1) is assigned to valuations based on unadjusted quoted
prices in active markets and the lowest priority (Level 3) is assigned to valuations based on
significant unobservable inputs.
In the determination of the classification of financial instruments in Level 2 or Level 3 of the fair
value hierarchy, the Plan considers all available information, including observable market data,
indications of market liquidity and orderliness, and its understanding of the valuation techniques
and significant inputs used. Judgments are made regarding the significance of the Level 3 inputs
to the instruments’ fair value measurement to its entirety. If unobservable inputs are considered
significant, the instrument is classified as Level 3.
There were no single issuers of plan investments exceeding 5% of total plan investments as of
December 31, 2024 and 2023.
The following is a description of the valuation methodologies used for assets measured at fair
value. There have been no changes in the methodologies used at December 31, 2024 and 2023.
Debt Securities predominantly include corporate debt securities and U.S. Treasury and federal
agency securities. U.S. Treasury securities are shown as Level 1. Corporate debt securities and
government agency securities are generally shown as Level 2. Debt securities are traded on a
national securities exchange, which are valued at the last reported sale price on the last business
day of the plan year and investments traded on the over-the-counter market and listed securities
for which no sale was reported on that date which are valued at the average of the last reported
bid and ask prices.
Investments in equity securities that are valued at quoted market prices are shown as Level 1.
Investments in privately held or thinly traded equity securities traded are shown as Level 3.
Investments in registered investment companies are valued at fair value based upon quoted prices
in an active market. Registered investment companies include money market funds, which are
priced at $1.00 per share.
Investments in collective investment funds are redeemable at NAV, which is the readily
determinable fair value. The price per share is quoted on a private market; however, the price per
share is based upon the value of the underlying investments, which are traded on an active
market.
Other investments predominantly include real estate and timber, venture capital and limited
partnerships, and hedge funds that are redeemable at NAV. The majority of these investments
are valued using NAV as a practical expedient. For certain other of these investments, the price
per share is quoted on a private market; however, the price per share is based upon the value of
the underlying investments, which are traded on an active market. Other investments also include
insurance contracts which are valued based on the contractual value (cash surrender value) as
provided by the issuer, and margin assets and cash collateral accounts that are priced at cost,
which approximates fair value.
The methods described above may produce a fair value calculation that may not be indicative of
net realizable value or reflective of future fair values. Furthermore, while the Plan believes its
valuation methods are appropriate and consistent with other market participants, the use of

(7) Financial Instruments with Off-Balance-Sheet Risk
In the normal course of business, the Plan may enter into transactions in various derivative
financial instruments with off-balance-sheet risk. The Plan may buy or sell interest rate futures
contracts or enter into swap transactions to protect against changes in the market. Payments are
made or received by the Plan equal to the changes in the contract value in accordance with
contract terms and are recorded as appreciation or depreciation. Due to the inherent volatility in
these financial instruments, the values of these financial instruments may change in the near
term, and these changes could differ materially from the amounts reported in the net assets of
the Plan.
Credit risk represents the potential loss to the Plan due to possible nonperformance by obligors
and counterparties of the terms of their contracts. Market risk represents the potential loss to
the Plan due to the decrease or increase in the value of an off-balance-sheet financial instrument
caused primarily by changes in interest rates or foreign exchange rates, or a combination thereof.
Forward contracts and futures represent commitments to purchase or sell securities, money
market instruments, or foreign currencies at a future date and at a specified price. Short sells
represent commitments to purchase securities at a future date and at a specified price. Both
credit and market risks exist with respect to forward contracts. Market risk exists with respect to
futures, short sells, and options. These positions are carried at current market value, and the
unrealized gains or losses are included in the net assets of the Plan. Financial futures and swaps

(9) Tax Status
The Internal Revenue Service (“IRS”) has issued a determination letter dated December 15, 2016
stating that the Plan qualifies under Section 401(a) of the IRC and that the Trust created
thereunder is exempt from federal income taxes under Section 501(a) of the IRC. The Plan
Sponsor believes that the Plan, as amended, continues to qualify and to operate in accordance
with applicable provisions of the IRC.
As a result of certain of the Plan’s investments, the Plan is subject to Unrelated Business Income
Taxes. Tax expense or benefit is included in administrative expenses.
Accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America require plan
management to evaluate tax positions taken by the Plan and recognize a tax liability (or asset) if
the organization has taken an uncertain position that more likely than not would not be sustained
upon examination by the IRS. The Plan Administrator has analyzed the tax positions taken by the
Plan, and has concluded that as of December 31, 2024, there are no uncertain positions taken or
expected to be taken that would require recognition of a liability (or asset) or disclosure in the
financial statements. The Plan is subject to routine audits by taxing jurisdictions; however, there
are currently no audits for any tax periods in progress. The Plan Administrator believes it is no
longer subject to income tax examinations for years prior to 2021.

(10) 401(h) Account
In addition to the normal retirement benefits, the Plan includes a medical-benefit component to
fund a portion of the postretirement obligations for retirees and their beneficiaries in accordance
with Section 401(h) of the IRC. A separate account has been established and maintained by the
Plan for the net assets related to the medical-benefit component (401(h) account). In accordance
with IRC Section 401(h), the Plan’s investments allocated to the 401(h) account may not be used
for, or diverted to, any purpose other than providing medical benefits for retirees and their
beneficiaries. Any assets transferred to the 401(h) account from the Plan in a qualified transfer of
excess pension plan assets (and any income allocable thereto) that are not used during the plan
year must be transferred out of the account to the Plan. The related obligations for medical
benefits are not included in this Plan’s present value of accumulated plan benefits but are
reflected as obligations in the financial statements of the Wells Fargo & Company Retiree Plan.
The net assets of the 401(h) account are restricted to fund a portion of postretirement medical
benefits for retirees and their beneficiaries in accordance with IRC Section 401(h). Plan
participants do not contribute to the 401(h) account. Employer contributions or qualified
transfers to the 401(h) account are determined annually and are at the discretion of the Plan
Sponsor. There were no employer contributions or qualified transfers to the 401(h) account for
the years ended December 31, 2024 and 2023, respectively.
(11) Nonexempt Prohibited Transaction
On January 2, 2024, the Trustee discovered that a Guaranteed Annuity Contract payment of
$160,978, intended for the Plan, was accidentally deposited into the Wells Fargo & Company
Employee Benefit Trust (“Master Trust”) on December 14, 2023. The Master Trust is used to fund
benefits for active employees under the Wells Fargo & Company Health Plan (for Eligible Active
Employees and their Dependents) and key retiree benefits under the Wells Fargo & Company
Retiree Plan. Upon discovery of the error, the Trustee moved the funds from the Master Trust to
the Plan Trust. On April 15, 2024, the Plan Sponsor deposited additional funds of $672 into the
Plan Trust to address any loss of earnings.

Changes in ERISA Methods/Assumptions Since the Prior Year
Method Changes
There have been no method changes in the funding valuation since the prior year.
Assumption Changes
The funding valuation reflects the following assumption changes:
• A change in the interest rate assumption from segment rates with a four-month lookback as of September
2021 to segment rates with a four-month lookback as of September 2022, each adjusted as applicable to
fall within the 25-year interest rate stabilization corridor.
• For legacy Wachovia participants, an update to the indexed cash balance interest crediting rate
assumption from 1.71% per year to 2.97% per year, based on a 24-month average of 10-year treasury
rates with a four-month lookback.
• For legacy Wells Fargo participants, an update to the indexed cash balance interest crediting rate
assumption from 2.87% per year to 3.33% per year, using a 24-month rolling three-month average of
30-year treasury rates with a four-month lookback and a floor of 2.83%.
• An update to the mortality and interest rates used for lump sum and cash balance conversions to the
applicable rates and mortality for the current plan year.
• The 2024-2025 retirement and withdrawal rates were adjusted to reflect updated displacement
expectations for 2024 as anticipated by Wells Fargo.
• A change in the expected rate of return on assets from 6.43% (limited to 5.74%) for the 2023 Plan Year
to 6.02% (limited to 5.59%) for the 2024 Plan Year based on Aon’s capital market assumptions and the
plan’s target asset allocation as of January 1, 2024. This change had no impact on the results presented
in this report.
Other than near-term retirement and withdrawal rate adjustments, the rationale for selecting the non-
prescribed assumptions used in the funding valuation is described in detail in the December 8, 2020
Actuarial Assumption Review meeting materials. Near-term retirement and withdrawal rate adjustments are
based on 2024 displacement expectations provided by Wells Fargo.
The assumption changes listed above (excluding those prescribed or indexed) did not reduce the funding
shortfall more than the thresholds stated in Internal Revenue Code Section 430(h)(5), so approval of the
Commissioner is not required.

Schedule SB, Part V — Summary of Plan Provisions
Plan Provisions—Merged Cash Balance Plan
Effective Date Effective July 1, 1999, the Norwest Corporation Pension
Plan was renamed the Wells Fargo & Company Cash
Balance Plan. The First Interstate Retirement Plan and
Century Business Credit Corporation Retirement Plan
were merged into this plan effective June 30, 1999. In
2000, the Michigan Financial and First Place Financial
Plans were merged into this plan. Effective
January 1, 2005, Wells Fargo Financial employees are
included in the plan.
As of December 31, 2007, all liabilities and assets from
the frozen Marquette, First Security, and Wells Fargo
Financial plans were merged into the
Wells Fargo & Company Cash Balance Plan.
As of June 30, 2009, the Wachovia Corporation Pension
Plan was merged into this plan.
The plan is frozen effective June 30, 2009. All benefit
accruals and pay credits cease as of this date.
The plan was last restated effective January 1, 2023 and
last amended effective December 1, 2023 (amendment
2023-02 executed October 12, 2023).
Participants Eligible employees of Wells Fargo & Company with one
year of service.
Normal Retirement
Eligibility Age 65.
Monthly Benefit The greater of (1) and (2), plus (3) below:
(1) (a) The accrued benefit based on participant's Wells
Fargo cash balance account, plus
(b) Any benefit earned under the Prior First Security
Plan, the Prior Marquette Plan, or the Prior Wells
Fargo Financial Plan;
(2) The benefit calculated under the Special Transition
Benefit for eligible former Norwest, Century, First
Interstate or Wells Fargo Financial participants;
(3) Any benefit earned under the Prior Wachovia
Corporation Plan.
Commencement Termination of employment, or later if elected.
